# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: eulerian-path-traversal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **bridge**, **isthmus**, **cut-edge**, or **cut arc** is an edge of a graph whose deletion increases the graph's number of connected components.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Equivalently, an edge is a bridge if and only if it is not contained in any cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] For a connected graph, a bridge can uniquely determine a cut.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] A graph is said to be **bridgeless** or **isthmus-free** if it contains no bridges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] This type of bridge should be distinguished from an unrelated meaning of "bridge" in graph theory, a subgraph separated from the rest of the graph by a specified subset of vertices; see bridge in the Glossary of graph theory.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] A graph with n nodes can contain at most $n-1$ bridges, since adding additional edges must create a cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] The graphs with exactly $n-1$ bridges are exactly the trees, and the graphs in which every edge is a bridge are exactly the forests.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] In every undirected graph, there is an equivalence relation on the vertices according to which two vertices are related to each other whenever there are two edge-disjoint paths connecting them.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] (Every vertex is related to itself via two length-zero paths, which are identical but nevertheless edge-disjoint.) The equivalence classes of this relation are called **2-edge-connected components**, and the bridges of the graph are exactly the edges whose endpoints belong to different components.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] The **bridge-block tree** of the graph has a vertex for every nontrivial component and an edge for every bridge.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Bridges are closely related to the concept of articulation vertices, vertices that belong to every path between some pair of other vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] The two endpoints of a bridge are articulation vertices unless they have a degree of 1, although it may also be possible for a non-bridge edge to have two articulation vertices as endpoints.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Analogously to bridgeless graphs being 2-edge-connected, graphs without articulation vertices are 2-vertex-connected.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] In a cubic graph, every cut vertex is an endpoint of at least one bridge.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] A **bridgeless graph** is a graph that does not have any bridges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Equivalent conditions are that each connected component of the graph has an open ear decomposition, that each connected component is 2-edge-connected, or (by Robbins' theorem) that every connected component has a strong orientation.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] An important open problem involving bridges is the cycle double cover conjecture, due to Seymour and Szekeres (1978 and 1979, independently), which states that every bridgeless graph admits a multi-set of simple cycles which contains each edge exactly twice.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] The first linear time algorithm (linear in the number of edges) for finding the bridges in a graph was described by Robert Tarjan in 1974.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] A very simple bridge-finding algorithm uses chain decompositions.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Chain decompositions are special ear decompositions depending on a DFS-tree *T* of *G* and can be computed very simply: Let every vertex be marked as unvisited.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] For each vertex *v* in ascending DFS-numbers 1...*n*, traverse every backedge (i.e. every edge not in the DFS tree) that is incident to *v* and follow the path of tree-edges back to the root of *T*, stopping at the first vertex that is marked as visited.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] During such a traversal, every traversed vertex is marked as visited.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Thus, a traversal stops at the latest at *v* and forms either a directed path or cycle, beginning with v; we call this path or cycle a *chain*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] The *i*th chain found by this procedure is referred to as *Ci*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] The following characterizations then allow to *read off* several properties of *G* from *C* efficiently, including all bridges of *G*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Let *C* be a chain decomposition of a simple connected graph *G=(V,E)*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] An edge *e* in *G* is a bridge if and only if *e* is not contained in any chain in *C*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] If *G* is 2-edge-connected, *C* is an ear decomposition.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] *G* is 2-vertex-connected if and only if *G* has minimum degree 2 and *C1* is the only cycle in *C*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] A vertex *v* in a 2-edge-connected graph *G* is a cut vertex if and only if *v* is the first vertex of a cycle in *C - C1*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] If *G* is 2-vertex-connected, *C* is an open ear decomposition.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Define an **Eulerian graph** as a graph with an Eulerian cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] This is because in an Eulerian graph every edge is a part of an Eulerian cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Hence, if the edge is deleted, then its endpoints remain connected through the rest of the cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Define an **almost Eulerian graph** as a graph that can be made Eulerian by adding a single edge (equivalently, a graph that contains an Eulerian trail).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] Every almost-Eulerian graph is almost-bridgeless, but the opposite is not true.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/bridge-graph-theory] The classes of bridgeless graphs and almost-Eulerian graphs have a non-empty intersection (the Eulerian graphs are both bridgeless and almost-Eulerian), but they do not contain each other.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] In graph theory, an **Eulerian trail** (or **Eulerian path**) is a trail in a finite graph that visits every edge exactly once (allowing for revisiting vertices).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Similarly, an **Eulerian circuit** or **Eulerian cycle** is an Eulerian trail that starts and ends on the same vertex.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] They were first discussed by Leonhard Euler while solving the famous Seven Bridges of Königsberg problem in 1736.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] ; i.e., a path starting and ending on the same vertex) that visits each edge exactly once?
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Euler proved that a necessary condition for the existence of Eulerian circuits is that all vertices in the graph have an even degree, and stated without proof that connected graphs with all vertices of even degree have an Eulerian circuit.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The first complete proof of this latter claim was published posthumously in 1873 by Carl Hierholzer.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] every vertex has an even number of incident edges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The term **Eulerian graph** has two common meanings in graph theory.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] One meaning is a graph with an Eulerian circuit, and the other is a graph with every vertex of even degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] These definitions coincide for connected graphs.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] For the existence of Eulerian trails it is necessary that zero or two vertices have an odd degree; this means the Königsberg graph is *not* Eulerian.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] If there are no vertices of odd degree, all Eulerian trails are circuits.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] If there are exactly two vertices of odd degree, all Eulerian trails start at one of them and end at the other.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] A graph that has an Eulerian trail but not an Eulerian circuit is called **semi-Eulerian**.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] An **Eulerian trail**, or **Euler walk**, in an undirected graph is a walk that uses each edge exactly once.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] If such a walk exists, the graph is called **traversable** or **semi-eulerian**.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] An **Eulerian cycle**, also called an **Eulerian circuit** or **Euler tour**, in an undirected graph is a circuit that uses each edge exactly once.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] If such a cycle exists, the graph is called **Eulerian** or **unicursal**.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The term "Eulerian graph" is also sometimes used in a weaker sense to denote a graph where every vertex has even degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] For finite connected graphs the two definitions are equivalent, while a possibly unconnected graph is Eulerian in the weaker sense if and only if each connected component has an Eulerian cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] For directed graphs, "path" has to be replaced with *directed path* and "cycle" with *directed cycle*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The definition and properties of Eulerian trails, cycles and graphs are valid for multigraphs as well.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] An **Eulerian orientation** of an undirected graph *G* is an assignment of a direction to each edge of *G* such that, at each vertex *v*, the indegree of *v* equals the outdegree of *v*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Such an orientation exists for any undirected graph in which every vertex has even degree, and may be found by constructing an Euler tour in each connected component of *G* and then orienting the edges according to the tour.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Every Eulerian orientation of a connected graph is a strong orientation, an orientation that makes the resulting directed graph strongly connected.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] While the *graph traversal* in Fleury's algorithm is linear in the number of edges, i.e. $O(|E|)$ , we also need to factor in the complexity of detecting bridges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] If we are to re-run Tarjan's linear time bridge-finding algorithm after the removal of every edge, Fleury's algorithm will have a time complexity of $O(|E|^{2})$ .
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] A dynamic bridge-finding algorithm of Thorup (2000) allows this to be improved to $O(|E|\cdot \log ^{3}|E|\cdot \log \log |E|)$ , but this is still significantly slower than alternative algorithms.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] This algorithm may also be implemented with a deque.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Because it is only possible to get stuck when the deque represents a closed tour, one should rotate the deque by removing edges from the tail and adding them to the head until unstuck, and then continue until all edges are accounted for.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The number of Eulerian circuits in a *directed graph* can be calculated using the so-called **BEST theorem**, named after de **B**ruijn, van Aardenne-**E**hrenfest, **S**mith and **T**utte.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The formula states that the number of Eulerian circuits in a digraph is the product of certain degree factorials and the number of rooted arborescences.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The latter can be computed as a determinant, by the matrix tree theorem, giving a polynomial time algorithm.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] BEST theorem is first stated in this form in a "note added in proof" to the Aardenne-Ehrenfest and de Bruijn paper (1951).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The original proof was bijective and generalized the de Bruijn sequences.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] It is a variation on an earlier result by Smith and Tutte (1941).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Counting the number of Eulerian circuits on *undirected graphs* is much more difficult.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] This problem is known to be #P-complete.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] A similar formula was later obtained by M.I.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Eulerian trails are used in bioinformatics to reconstruct the DNA sequence from its fragments.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] They are also used in CMOS circuit design to find an optimal logic gate ordering.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] There are some algorithms for processing trees that rely on an Euler tour of the tree (where each edge is treated as a pair of arcs).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The de Bruijn sequences can be constructed as Eulerian trails of de Bruijn graphs.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] In an infinite graph, the corresponding concept to an Eulerian trail or Eulerian cycle is an Eulerian line, a doubly-infinite trail that covers all of the edges of the graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] It is not sufficient for the existence of such a trail that the graph be connected and that all vertex degrees be even; for instance, the infinite Cayley graph shown, with all vertex degrees equal to four, has no Eulerian line.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The infinite graphs that contain Eulerian lines were characterized by Erdős, Grünwald & Weiszfeld (1936).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Euler stated a necessary condition for a finite graph to be Eulerian as all vertices must have even degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Hierholzer proved this is a sufficient condition in a paper published in 1873.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] This leads to the following necessary and sufficient statement for what a finite graph must have to be Eulerian: An undirected connected finite graph is Eulerian if and only if every vertex of G has even degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The following result was proved by Veblen in 1912: An undirected connected graph is Eulerian if and only if it is the disjoint union of some cycles.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Hierholzer developed a linear time algorithm for constructing an Eulerian tour in an undirected graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] It is possible to have a directed graph that has all even out-degrees but is not Eulerian.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Since an Eulerian circuit leaves a vertex the same number of times as it enters that vertex, a necessary condition for an Eulerian circuit to exist is that the in-degree and out-degree are equal at each vertex.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Obviously, connectivity is also necessary.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] König proved that these conditions are also sufficient.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] That is, a directed graph is Eulerian if and only if it is connected and the in-degree and out-degree are equal at each vertex.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] In this theorem it doesn't matter whether "connected" means "weakly connected" or "strongly connected" since they are equivalent for Eulerian graphs.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Hierholzer's linear time algorithm for constructing an Eulerian tour is also applicable to directed graphs.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] All mixed graphs that are both even and symmetric are guaranteed to be Eulerian.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] However, this is not a necessary condition, as it is possible to construct a non-symmetric, even graph that is Eulerian.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] The process of checking if a mixed graph is Eulerian is harder than checking if an undirected or directed graph is Eulerian because the balanced set condition concerns every possible subset of vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/eulerian-path] Every Eulerian graph is a bridgeless graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] In graph theory, the **handshaking lemma** is the statement that, in every finite undirected graph, the number of vertices that touch an odd number of edges is even.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] For example, if there is a party of people who shake hands, the number of people who shake an odd number of other people's hands is even.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The handshaking lemma is a consequence of the **degree sum formula**, also sometimes called the handshaking lemma, according to which the sum of the degrees (the numbers of times each vertex is touched) equals twice the number of edges in the graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Both results were proven by Leonhard Euler (1736) in his famous paper on the Seven Bridges of Königsberg that began the study of graph theory.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Beyond the Seven Bridges of Königsberg Problem, which subsequently formalized Eulerian Tours, other applications of the degree sum formula include proofs of certain combinatorial structures.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] For example, in the proofs of Sperner's lemma and the mountain climbing problem the geometric properties of the formula commonly arise.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The complexity class PPA encapsulates the difficulty of finding a second odd vertex, given one such vertex in a large implicitly-defined graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] An undirected graph consists of a system of vertices, and edges connecting unordered pairs of vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] In any graph, the degree $\deg(v)$ of a vertex v is defined as the number of edges that have v as an endpoint.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] For graphs that are allowed to contain loops connecting a vertex to itself, a loop should be counted as contributing two units to the degree of its endpoint for the purposes of the handshaking lemma.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Then, the handshaking lemma states that, in every finite graph, there must be an even number of vertices for which $\deg(v)$ is an odd number.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The vertices of odd degree in a graph are sometimes called **odd nodes** (or **odd vertices**); in this terminology, the handshaking lemma can be rephrased as the statement that every graph has an even number of odd nodes.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The degree sum formula states that $\sum _{v\in V}\deg v=2|E|,$ where V is the set of nodes (or vertices) in the graph and E is the set of edges in the graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] That is, the sum of the vertex degrees equals twice the number of edges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] In directed graphs, another form of the degree-sum formula states that the sum of in-degrees of all vertices, and the sum of out-degrees, both equal the number of edges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Here, the in-degree is the number of incoming edges, and the out-degree is the number of outgoing edges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] A version of the degree sum formula also applies to finite families of sets or, equivalently, multigraphs: the sum of the degrees of the elements (where the degree equals the number of sets containing it) always equals the sum of the cardinalities of the sets.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Both results also apply to any subgraph of the given graph and in particular to its connected components.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] A consequence is that, for any odd vertex, there must exist a path connecting it to another odd vertex.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Leonhard Euler first proved the handshaking lemma in his work on the Seven Bridges of Königsberg, asking for a walking tour of the city of Königsberg (now Kaliningrad) crossing each of its seven bridges once.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Euler stated the fundamental results for this problem in terms of the number of odd vertices in the graph, which the handshaking lemma restricts to be an even number.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] If this number is zero, an Euler tour exists, and if it is two, an Euler path exists.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Otherwise, the problem cannot be solved.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] In the case of the Seven Bridges of Königsberg, the graph representing the problem has four odd vertices, and has neither an Euler path nor an Euler tour.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] It was therefore impossible to tour all seven bridges in Königsberg without repeating a bridge.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Several combinatorial structures may be shown to be even in number by relating them to the odd vertices in an appropriate "exchange graph".
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Smith proved, in any cubic graph G there must be an even number of Hamiltonian cycles through any fixed edge $uv$ ; these are cycles that pass through each vertex exactly once.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Thomason (1978) used a proof based on the handshaking lemma to extend this result to graphs in which all vertices have odd degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Thomason defines an exchange graph H , the vertices of which are in one-to-one correspondence with the Hamiltonian paths in G beginning at u and continuing through edge $uv$ .
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Two such paths $p_{1}$ and $p_{2}$ are defined as being connected by an edge in H if one may obtain $p_{2}$ by adding a new edge to the end of $p_{1}$ and removing another edge from the middle of $p_{1}$ .
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] This operation is reversible, forming a symmetric relation, so H is an undirected graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Since H has an even number of odd vertices, G must have an even number of Hamiltonian cycles through $uv$ .
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The handshaking lemma (or degree sum formula) are also used in proofs of several other results in mathematics.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Euler's proof of the degree sum formula uses the technique of double counting: he counts the number of incident pairs $(v,e)$ where e is an edge and vertex v is one of its endpoints, in two different ways.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Vertex v belongs to $\deg(v)$ pairs, where $\deg(v)$ (the degree of v ) is the number of edges incident to it.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Therefore, the number of incident pairs is the sum of the degrees.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] However, each edge in the graph belongs to exactly two incident pairs, one for each of its endpoints; therefore, the number of incident pairs is $2|E|$ .
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Since these two formulas count the same set of objects, they must have equal values.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The same proof can be interpreted as summing the entries of the incidence matrix of the graph in two ways, by rows to get the sum of degrees and by columns to get twice the number of edges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] For graphs, the handshaking lemma follows as a corollary of the degree sum formula.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] In a sum of integers, the parity of the sum is not affected by the even terms in the sum; the overall sum is even when there is an even number of odd terms, and odd when there is an odd number of odd terms.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Since one side of the degree sum formula is the even number $2|E|$ , the sum on the other side must have an even number of odd terms; that is, there must be an even number of odd-degree vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] , regular of degree five, has an even number of vertices (16) and a number of edges (40) that is a multiple of five.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The degree sum formula implies that every r -regular graph with n vertices has $nr/2$ edges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Because the number of edges must be an integer, it follows that when r is odd the number of vertices must be even.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Additionally, for odd values of r , the number of edges must be divisible by r .
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] A bipartite graph has its vertices split into two subsets, with each edge having one endpoint in each subset.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] It follows from the same double counting argument that, in each subset, the sum of degrees equals the number of edges in the graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] In particular, both subsets have equal degree sums.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] For biregular graphs, with a partition of the vertices into subsets $V_{1}$ and $V_{2}$ with every vertex in a subset $V_{i}$ having degree $r_{i}$ , it must be the case that $|V_{1}|r_{1}=|V_{2}|r_{2}$ ; both equal the number of edges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The handshaking lemma does not apply in its usual form to infinite graphs, even when they have only a finite number of odd-degree vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] For instance, an infinite path graph with one endpoint has only a single odd-degree vertex rather than having an even number of such vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] However, it is possible to formulate a version of the handshaking lemma using the concept of an end, an equivalence class of semi-infinite paths ("rays") considering two rays as equivalent when there exists a third ray that uses infinitely many vertices from each of them.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] The degree of an end is the maximum number of edge-disjoint rays that it contains, and an end is odd if its degree is finite and odd.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] More generally, it is possible to define an end as being odd or even, regardless of whether it has infinite degree, in graphs for which all vertices have finite degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Then, in such graphs, the number of odd vertices and odd ends, added together, is either even or infinite.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] By a theorem of Gallai the vertices of any graph can be partitioned as $V=V_{e}\cup V_{o}$ where in the two resulting induced subgraphs, $G[V_{e}]$ has all degrees even and $G[V_{o}]$ has all degrees odd.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Here, $|V_{o}|$ must be even by the handshaking lemma.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] It is also possible to find even-degree and odd-degree induced subgraphs with many vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] An induced subgraph of even degree can be found with at least half of the vertices, and an induced subgraph of odd degree (in a graph with no isolated vertices) can be found with $|V_{o}|/|V|>1/10000$ .
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] In connection with the exchange graph method for proving the existence of combinatorial structures, it is of interest to ask how efficiently these structures may be found.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] For instance, suppose one is given as input a Hamiltonian cycle in a cubic graph; it follows from Smith's theorem that there exists a second cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] How quickly can this second cycle be found?
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Papadimitriou (1994) investigated the computational complexity of questions such as this, or more generally of finding a second odd-degree vertex when one is given a single odd vertex in a large implicitly-defined graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/handshaking-lemma] Computational problems proven to be complete for the complexity class PPA include computational tasks related to Sperner's lemma and to fair subdivision of resources according to the Hobby–Rice theorem.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] In graph theory and combinatorial optimization, **Guan's route problem**, the **Chinese postman problem**, **postman tour** or **route inspection problem** is to find a shortest closed path or circuit that visits every edge of an (connected) undirected graph at least once.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] When the graph has an Eulerian circuit (a closed walk that covers every edge once), that circuit is an optimal solution.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] Otherwise, the optimization problem is to find the smallest number of graph edges to duplicate (or the subset of edges with the minimum possible total weight) so that the resulting multigraph does have an Eulerian circuit.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] It can be solved in polynomial time, unlike the Travelling Salesman Problem which is NP-hard.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] It is different from the Travelling Salesman Problem in that the travelling salesman cannot repeat visited nodes and does not have to visit every edge.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] The problem was originally studied by the Chinese mathematician Meigu Guan in 1960, whose Chinese paper was translated into English in 1962.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] The original name "Chinese postman problem" was coined in his honor; different sources credit the coinage either to Alan J.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] Goldman or Jack Edmonds, both of whom were at the U.S.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] National Bureau of Standards at the time.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] A generalization takes as input any set *T* of evenly many vertices, and must produce as output a minimum-weight edge set in the graph whose odd-degree vertices are precisely those of *T*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] This problem, the ***T*-join problem**, is also solvable in polynomial time by the same approach that solves the postman problem.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] The undirected route inspection problem can be solved in polynomial time by an algorithm based on the concept of a *T*-join.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] Let *T* be a set of vertices in a graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] An edge set *J* is called a *T***-join** if the collection of vertices that have an odd number of incident edges in *J* is exactly the set *T*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] A *T*-join exists whenever every connected component of the graph contains an even number of vertices in *T*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] The *T***-join problem** is to find a *T*-join with the minimum possible number of edges or the minimum possible total weight.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] For any *T*, a smallest *T*-join (when it exists) necessarily consists of ${\tfrac {1}{2}}|T|$ paths that join the vertices of *T* in pairs.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] The paths will be such that the total length or total weight of all of them is as small as possible.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] In an optimal solution, no two of these paths will share any edge, but they may have shared vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] A minimum *T*-join can be obtained by constructing a complete graph on the vertices of *T*, with edges that represent shortest paths in the given input graph, and then finding a minimum weight perfect matching in this complete graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] The edges of this matching represent paths in the original graph, whose union forms the desired *T*-join.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] Both constructing the complete graph, and then finding a matching in it, can be done in O(*n*3) computational steps.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] For the route inspection problem, *T* should be chosen as the set of all odd-degree vertices.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] By the assumptions of the problem, the whole graph is connected (otherwise no tour exists), and by the handshaking lemma it has an even number of odd vertices, so a *T*-join always exists.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] Doubling the edges of a *T*-join causes the given graph to become an Eulerian multigraph (a connected graph in which every vertex has even degree), from which it follows that it has an Euler tour, a tour that visits each edge of the multigraph exactly once.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] This tour will be an optimal solution to the route inspection problem.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] On a directed graph, the same general ideas apply, but different techniques must be used.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] If the directed graph is Eulerian, one need only find an Euler cycle.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] If it is not, one must find *T*-joins, which in this case entails finding paths from vertices with an in-degree greater than their out-degree to those with an out-degree greater than their in-degree such that they would make in-degree of every vertex equal to its out-degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] This can be solved as an instance of the minimum-cost flow problem in which there is one unit of supply for every unit of excess in-degree, and one unit of demand for every unit of excess out-degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] As such it is solvable in O(|*V*|2|*E*|) time.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] A solution exists if and only if the given graph is strongly connected.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] Various combinatorial problems have been reduced to the Chinese Postman Problem, including finding a maximum cut in a planar graph and a minimum-mean length circuit in an undirected graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/route-inspection-problem] A few variants of the Chinese Postman Problem have been studied and shown to be NP-complete.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The **Seven Bridges of Königsberg** is a historical puzzle asking for a walking tour through the bridges of the city of Königsberg (now Kaliningrad in Russia) that is a circuit ending where it started.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Its mathematical formalization and proof of impossibility by Leonhard Euler, in 1736, laid the foundations of graph theory and foreshadowed the idea of topology.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The city of Königsberg in Prussia (now Kaliningrad, Russia) was set on both sides of the Pregel River, and included two large islands—Kneiphof and Lomse—which were connected to each other, and to the two mainland portions of the city—Altstadt and Vorstadt—by seven bridges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The problem was to devise a walk through the city that would cross each of those bridges once and only once.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Euler proved that the problem has no solution.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The difficulty he faced was the development of a suitable technique of analysis, and of subsequent tests that established this assertion with mathematical rigor.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Euler first pointed out that the choice of route inside each land mass is irrelevant and that the only important feature of a route is the sequence of bridges crossed.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] This allowed him to reformulate the problem in abstract terms (laying the foundations of graph theory), eliminating all features except the list of land masses and the bridges connecting them.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] In modern terms, one replaces each land mass with an abstract "vertex" or node, and each bridge with an abstract connection, an "edge", which only serves to record which pair of vertices (land masses) is connected by that bridge.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The resulting mathematical structure is a graph.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Since only the connection information is relevant, the shape of pictorial representations of a graph may be distorted in any way, without changing the graph itself.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Only the number of edges (possibly zero) between each pair of nodes is significant.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] It does not, for instance, matter whether the edges drawn are straight or curved, or whether one node is to the left or right of another.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Next, Euler observed that (except at the endpoints of the walk), whenever one enters a vertex by a bridge, one leaves the vertex by a bridge.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] In other words, during any walk in the graph, the number of times one enters a non-terminal vertex equals the number of times one leaves it.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] However, all four of the land masses in the original problem are touched by an *odd* number of bridges (one is touched by 5 bridges, and each of the other three is touched by 3).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Since, at most, two land masses can serve as the endpoints of a walk, the proposition of a walk traversing each bridge once leads to a contradiction.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] In modern language, Euler shows that the possibility of a walk through a graph, traversing each edge exactly once, depends on the degrees of the nodes.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The degree of a node is the number of edges touching it.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Euler's argument shows that a necessary condition for the walk of the desired form is that the graph be connected and have exactly zero or two nodes of odd degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] This condition turns out also to be sufficient—a result stated by Euler and later proved by Carl Hierholzer.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Such a walk is now called an *Eulerian trail* or *Euler walk* in his honor.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Further, if there are nodes of odd degree, then any Eulerian path will start at one of them and end at the other.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Since the graph corresponding to historical Königsberg has four nodes of odd degree, it cannot have an Eulerian path.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] An alternative form of the problem asks for a path that traverses all bridges and also has the same starting and ending point.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Such a walk is called an *Eulerian circuit* or an *Euler tour*.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Such a circuit exists if, and only if, the graph is connected and all nodes have even degree.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] All Eulerian circuits are also Eulerian paths, but not all Eulerian paths are Eulerian circuits.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Petersburg Academy on 26 August 1735, and published as *Solutio problematis ad geometriam situs pertinentis* (The solution of a problem relating to the geometry of position) in the journal *Commentarii academiae scientiarum Petropolitanae* in 1741.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] It is available in English translation in *The World of Mathematics* by James R.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] In the history of mathematics, Euler's solution of the Königsberg bridge problem is considered to be the first theorem of graph theory and the first true proof in the network theory, a subject now generally regarded as a branch of combinatorics.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Combinatorial problems of other types such as the enumeration of permutations and combinations had been considered since antiquity.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Euler's recognition that the key information was the number of bridges and the list of their endpoints (rather than their exact positions) presaged the development of topology.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The difference between the actual layout and the graph schematic is a good example of the idea that topology is not concerned with the rigid shape of objects.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Hence, as Euler recognized, the "geometry of position" is not about "measurements and calculations" but about something more general.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] That called in question the traditional Aristotelian view that mathematics is the "science of quantity".
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Though that view fits arithmetic and Euclidean geometry, it did not fit topology and the more abstract structural features studied in modern mathematics.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Philosophers have noted that Euler's proof is not about an abstraction or a model of reality, but directly about the real arrangement of bridges.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Hence the certainty of mathematical proof can apply directly to reality.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The proof is also explanatory, giving insight into why the result must be true.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Two of the seven original bridges did not survive the bombing of Königsberg in World War II.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Two others were later demolished and replaced by a highway.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The three other bridges remain, although only two of them are from Euler's time (one was rebuilt in 1935).
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] These changes leave five bridges existing at the same sites that were involved in Euler's problem.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] In terms of graph theory, two of the nodes now have degree 2, and the other two have degree 3.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Therefore, an Eulerian path is now possible, but it must begin on one island and end on the other.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The University of Canterbury in Christchurch has incorporated a model of the bridges into a grass area between the old Physical Sciences Library and the Erskine Building, housing the Departments of Mathematics, Statistics and Computer Science.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] The rivers are replaced with short bushes and the central island sports a stone tōrō.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Rochester Institute of Technology has incorporated the puzzle into the pavement in front of the Gene Polisseni Center, an ice hockey arena that opened in 2014, and the Georgia Institute of Technology also installed a landscape art model of the seven bridges in 2018.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] A popular variant of the puzzle is the Bristol Bridges Walk.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] Like historical Königsberg, Bristol occupies two river banks and two river islands.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] However, the configuration of the 45 major bridges in Bristol is such that an Eulerian circuit exists.
[src:eulerian-path-traversal/seven-bridges-of-königsberg] This cycle has been popularized by a book and news coverage and has featured in different charity events.
